Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law on the introduction of administrative responsibility for the violation of the time and procedure of payment of goods (works, services) when making purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to address the very acute problem of non-fulfilment of their obligations by customers in the implementation of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already executed state and municipal contracts was ubiquitous.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General’s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who entered into unfunded contracts, tried to evade payment obligations and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the Prosecutor’s Office submitted 9,7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4,5 thousand officials were brought to disciplinary liability, to the administrative - 533, to the investigative bodies for the organization of procedural inspections.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
And these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs have resulted in much more modest amounts.
Here's a typical case.
The head of a small company won the competition for the provision of social transport services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled the obligations, but did not receive the money in time.
The result is a growing financial pile of debt on salaries, taxes, loans, which would lead to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur did not seek help from the prosecutor's office.
Now, in some regions, the problem has been managed to level as much as possible.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by prosecutors of entities of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where indebtedness rates continue to reach critical levels, the Prosecutor’s Office operates under manual crisis management.
The Prosecutor-General personally conducts exit meetings with representatives of local authorities, at which all violations discovered by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are subjectively discussed.
Such operational meetings this year have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
To improve the payment discipline of public customers will be able to implement the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in Part of the Establishment of Administrative Responsibility of the Customer's Officials and the Order of Purchases for the violation of the term and procedure of payment of goods (work)
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the time and procedure for payment of goods, works and services in public and municipal procurement.
And if the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, he is awaiting disqualification for a period of one year to two years.
All prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novellas in practice.
Civil Rights Protection Group Announces Warning on Movement in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population issued a warning to colored people traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and attacks on racist grounds.
The statement of the group reads as follows: "Warning for the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population, valid until August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, guests and citizens of the state of Missouri to be particularly attentive and to exercise increased caution in allocating pilgrimages to the staff.
According to the National Association for Promoting the Advancement of the Colored Population, the group’s announcement of a movement warning was prompted by a recently passed law in Missouri that made it harder for people to win discrimination-related lawsuits, as well as the fact that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately often choose their targets.
“You have people who are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of their skin, beaten and killed," Rod Chapell, president of the National Association to Promote the Progress of the Colored Population of Missouri, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization against the U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-eight-year-old Tori Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gasoline while on a state tour, and Missouri State Police arrested him without bringing any charges of the crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office that said black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The goal of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
“People should be prepared one way or another, whether they take money with them for collateral or report to relatives that they are traveling through the state territory.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s Hate Crime Reporting Program, there were 100 hate crimes in Missouri in 2015, making it the sixteenth state in the state in the number of hate crimes.
The motion warning is also a response to a new law in the state of Missouri that will make it more difficult to sue a legal person for housing or employment discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Protection Union (ACLU) issued warnings to travelers in Texas and Arizona after these states passed new immigration control laws, under which local law enforcement agencies were ordered to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which, according to ACLU, was due to increase the number of people arrested for violating immigration laws.
