Facebook Critics’ Blocking: Don’t Stand Up for a Public Position if You’re Unwilling to Listen to Criticism from Voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
The Americans loved George Washington, but that didn’t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
His criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he didn’t shut his mouth to critics.
In 1783, Washington said, “It is possible to deprive freedom of speech, and we, the deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter.”
Now I'm going to go to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and deleted posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor’s subordinates called the claim null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of “well and what.”
“It’s just Facebook,” many will say.
But it's also important.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a remarkably popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
It is second in the approval rating among 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has demonstrated a firm hand in the management of the state and a commitment to its principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as the primary way to communicate with his constituents and jokes about his bald head after chemotherapy on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and is run by the administration for taxpayers' money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Chess defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply moderating them.
But it's too easy - to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters who are rogue on the Internet.
"Post" spoke to some of the real people that Hogan blocked.
And these are the real people, not the trolls, the teacher, the businessman, the pastor, who address their elected leaders.
They all say that their comments were respectful, substantive and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to Hogan to be Catholic.
Lakshmi’s lawyer, Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite commentary that I am disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comments section of the post.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it’s a so-called rant, instead of admitting that they’re dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life stance.”
In the age of Facebook, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or deleting negative comments.
This is much less dusty work than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical edges, or arresting and shutting down protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening now, just in numbers.
Hoggen is not the first official to be criticized for not listening to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Casheris, the chairman of the Laudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by banning the voter from his Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin has filed claims by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal spending was about the same as today’s Internet.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers grew fourfold, and the authors of anonymous letters greatly undermined his authority.
And even then Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the aliases "Yuricola", "Valerius", "Belizarius" and "Portius" wrote letters to newspapers ridiculing Washington's decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the online George Washington Papers project, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his stance on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he didn’t try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech is at the heart of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to it.
