Poverty and Death in Indonesia's 'Golden Land'
When preparing lunch, Bardin Degei does not use the stove.
It is rarely used even in pots.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually simply places a sweet potato, which here is called a "note", right in the focal point.
After half an hour, the charred tubers are caught and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the ground floor – she has no furniture – and it is here that she does her homework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The bathroom serves as a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Plurality is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one decides to walk around the village after five in the evening,” she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of the occupying troops.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the government of Jakarta, which maintains tight control of the region without allowing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapur, the administrative center of the province, to Nabir, and then a five-hour shaking in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The city with a population of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; corrugated steel roofs are painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few of the Indonesians, not to mention journalists, and almost none of the foreigners arrived here.
Prior to the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshiped a god named Uga Tamei.
There were other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear this dress,” Degei says, pointing to her bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt, and bright shirt.
“In the past, we only had leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy levels among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesian gold.
The world’s largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is only sixty miles from Paniai, a high-altitude province roughly the size of New Jersey, where 153,000 people live.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion in gold and copper.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves, the value of which is estimated at $78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful armed forces retain their stifling presence here.
According to an investigation by the New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local servicemen and units nearly $20 million, including up to $150,000 per officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this goldmine and are mercilessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and deprived of their liberty.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killing of indigenous people in the highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” the report, published in 2016, by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture — especially frequent, as is demonstrated in another report, rape and electric shock.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because accidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
Nuts have been protracted as Papua’s resources have attracted influxes of migrants from other areas of Indonesia.
The province’s 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan banks, "varungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gado-gado", served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
“Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than the indigenous people of Papua,” explains Abeth You, a twenty-four-year-old native of Paniai, who moved to Jayapur, the provincial administrative center, for work.
“Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua, the mother-mother (women) of Papua, have lost their market.”
Indonesian President Joko Vidodo, known to the people as Jokowi, vowed to deal with inequality and rights violations in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter secured the support of 27 of Papua’s 29 counties, including Paniai.
But in Papua almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokovy, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” Jou said.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokovi Paniai experienced the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas hymns at the fire in Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Thebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and witnesses, the soldiers, who were drunk, chased the children and beat them with examples of rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julian Aimo, was so severely beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a government building near the election commission, and the next day the situation worsened.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the vaita, the dance of the Papuan tribe of Mee Pago: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began to throw stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation inflamed, the soldiers on the internal radio were given the order: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them", - so he sounded, as stated in the official document, which was seen by the correspondents of the magazine "TIME", but which was not published in the local.
Fifty-six-year-old Eremias Kayama, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, felt the approach of danger and called for calm, appealing to the crowd with a request to disperse around the house.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who shot, but says the bullet came from the sherring of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
The local resident Alfius Jouva was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johanes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME magazine.
“I saw that he was dead...I kissed him.”
General Yotge Mende, Papua’s senior police inspector, told reporters that his officers were only “defending” their base because it was under attack.
“We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” said Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistio in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters have been killed and many more injured.
The news of the murders reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a heartfelt speech in Jayapur in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historic abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately, so that it will never happen again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to put an end to historic human rights violations.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
“Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 1990s or early 1990s.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed,” he said.
Viranto then renounced his words, speaking to Time magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he did not plan to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through the court.”
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the bloody 1999 independence vote in East Timor, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims from Paniai encountered such statements with murky mistrust.
“I have been questioned four times over the past three years, but there has been absolutely no change,” says Johannes.
“I am tired.”
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid I’m going to be arrested by the military, I’m afraid I’m going to be shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Pannaya were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury the four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting didn't stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in the Paniai district of Deiyai.
During the clash between the villagers and the manager of the construction company, who refused to help bring a man who was unconscious to the hospital, one person died and another 17 were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the office of the construction site owned by the company.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at officers, who in response fired warning shots.
But locals claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retribution,” twenty-nine-year-old Domingu Badia, who lives near the hospital, told TIME magazine and saw how they were rushing to deliver the wounded.
“I hid at home for two days.”
Deijai demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account and the mobile police brigade recalled from the region.
Paniai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development is caused by the dissatisfaction of the Mee, Monks, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green central highland areas of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend Papuan rights by arranging sporadic attacks and assaults with kidnappings on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the senior OPM leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yoga and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and unjustifiably detained in Paniai in recent years under the pretext of “protecting national independence.”
Some of them never came back.
Among the population of Papua, Paniai is considered a “sad, forgotten place”.
Poverty intensifies discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is not available to the same extent.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly a note, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold at the local market.
Ten club notes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic disparities between indigenous Papuans and new migrants, who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to the airport of Nabire, have increased.
Few existing vacancies are usually given to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village ... because there is no work or money here,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of the international media remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudi and Basil Longshan were deported from Papua for “insufficient coherence with the relevant organizations” despite being granted rare video recording permits.
According to Felim Kine, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, the promises made during the Jokovi campaign to lift restrictions on the work of the media in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Now, foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern provinces of Indonesia, Papua and West Papua, face new dangers: visa waivers and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of attention from the press means that international pressure on the Government of Indonesia is largely limited to Papua’s immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – appealed to the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “diverse and widespread violations” in Papua, including the shooting in Panaya.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanat Nasir declined the group’s statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that “In Indonesia there is still a democratic system and there is a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights violations.”
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Dutch human rights ambassador Kees Van Baaar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals broke the silence, please: “We want freedom”, as the source, who was also present at the meeting, claims, but wanted to stay.
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but the Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Djokovic again.
“The Jokowi are a man who has good intentions, but is surrounded by people involved in the shooting in Paniai,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribe’s council.
He wants Djokovic to know that the inhabitants of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat from the greedy army, are plunged into poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Gobai says that the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their voice given to Jokovi to be a debt that he has to pay.
“They don’t need money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite the threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims in the plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not allow the guilty to forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” Jacobus says without raising his head.
“What else did we have to do?”
