Head of EPA Pruitt Rejects Intention to Delay Compliance with Obama’s Emissions Reduction Rules
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency reversed his decision to postpone the implementation of Obama's rules aimed at reducing emissions of polluting substances that lead to the formation of smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by saying that his agency now listens more than in previous administrations to the needs of individual states’ environmental regulators.
He did not mention the lawsuit against his previous position filed with the Federal Court of Appeal.
The dispute unfolded around the October 1 deadline, to which states must ensure compliance with the 2015 ground-level ozone standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would defer their compliance by one year to give his office more time to study the plan and avoid “non-compliance with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.”
Pruitt, who before he was appointed by President Trump to his current position, was the Attorney General of Oklahoma, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental standards.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or postponed the introduction of norms that the chemical or gas-oil industry opposed.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Pyuitt to return to the old norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA exceeded his authority in trying to delay the Obama administration’s enforcement of a rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released on Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that by abruptly changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s duty to cooperate with states in a comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
“In previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet the deadlines set, then awaited lawsuits from activist groups and others, and discussed the deadlines in the course of the settlement,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous post.
“We don’t believe in regulation through court proceedings, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our charter and the power it gives us.”
However, the EPA statement said that Pruitt could at some point re-use its “deferral powers and other data by law” to make sure that the rules “jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader revision of the rules on ozone.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to postpone the implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on this issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that filed lawsuits against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
“Changing the EPA’s course – after our lawsuits – is an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the smog covering their cities,” Schneiderman said.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia.
Ozone at ground level occurs when conventional pollutants from machines, power plants, oil refineries, and chemical plants and other sources enter the atmosphere in response to sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause severe breathing problems in people sensitive to it, leading to thousands of premature deaths a year.
Health advocates and environmentalists welcomed the unexpected change in Pruitt’s course.
“It’s sad to think about how much pressure it took to achieve this perfectly logical step from the person assigned to protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to resist the Trump administration’s ideological campaign and protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.”
