New test results to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden have been published
Recent results from asylum-seekers in Sweden who were subjected to a new method of medical assessment of age show that more than 80 percent of those tested were evaluated as persons over 18 years of age, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) began testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the assessment of age in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) criticized for failing to determine the actual age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, the Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were assessed as people 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the forensic agency assessed that the tested “probably a person 18 years of age or older.”
In the case of 432 cases, the conclusion stated that the person "probably less than 18".
The tests are only carried out in cases where the age of the person raises doubts.
According to Johan Geransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are in line with the results of the past months.
“We don’t see a big difference from the statistics over the past few months, the numbers are quite consistent,” he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, "it is likely that the age of the tested person is 18 years or older."
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper "Svenska Dagbladet" found that in 243 cases the person openly stated that he is performing 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which consists of x-raying wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and giving them to dentists and radiologists for analysis, has also been criticized in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist from the Carolina Institute Claude Marcus, part of whose work is to assess the biological maturity of people in order to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don’t think we should use the measurement methods that are being used now.
The biological age is thus determined very precisely.
If we can’t define it with confidence, we shouldn’t pretend that we can,” he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Geransen of the Forensic Medicine Agency said in favor of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk is wrong to take a child for an adult toddler.
