The order and place of the oath shall be determined by the President.
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the President - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law have been developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, MPs planned to directly determine the procedure for swearing in the law.
Children under the age of 18, as well as incapable, will be exempted from the solemn oath, it follows from the revised text of amendments to the draft law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available at the disposal of "Izvestii"), which the committee will consider before the second reading at its meeting on July 11.
The idea of introducing an oath of citizenship of the Russian Federation instead of the formal signing of documents, President Vladimir Putin supported on June 6 during a meeting with the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodymyr.
The deputies have drafted this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the draft law, which provides for the annulment of the decision on the extradition of citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, the Internet.
According to the bill, his logic was this: by issuing citizenship documents, a person signs a promise to comply with Russian legislation - he has taken the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The bill was introduced in the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergey Mironov ("Fair Russia") and the Speaker of the General Assembly Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it at first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill at second reading, but now it has been revised again.
Now it says that the procedure for taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", specifying that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state coat of arms and the flag of Russia in the presence of the representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where it is possible to place the coat of arms of the Russian Federation is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state bodies of subjects, municipal entities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could also be ZAGS.
A solemn oath will be taken by those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship after officials have checked their documents.
But the Russian passport a person will receive only after taking the oath, it follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
In the updated text, it is said that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, not from the age of 14.
The rule has been maintained that incapacitated or incapacitated persons, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the text of the oath by hand, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and "other persons",
Also, the updated bill prescribes a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of residents of Ukraine, who are considered to be native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to formally renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
The renunciation of "foreign" citizenship, as it is now, will not be necessary if it is provided for in an international treaty or if it is not possible "for reasons not dependent on the person".
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among them the first Deputy Speaker of DG Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for the decision of their fate on the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the head of the Duma committee on state construction and legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (ER).
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have in writing refused “other” citizenship and handed over the former passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but “for reasons not dependent on it” it has not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be accepted to work in facilities and organizations, whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country may not become a member of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should come into force from 1 September 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws must be prepared.
