Joan Lee, a former banker with a passion for real estate repairs, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a nice typical house in the style of Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not collect her belongings and did not move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger square,” Joan says.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price the same day.”
From the moment of first viewing, the apartment with an area of 1000 square feet has undergone a complete reconstruction.
Initially, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-story to squeeze the maximum benefit from the generous ceiling height.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill’s Duck & Shed architectural and design studio to use 12.5-foot-high ceilings to create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would be useful to Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to arrange two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-story where one could stand at full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We had to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other and did not have to bend.
It was not only necessary to build a simple platform, but also to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allow the use of the premises above and below.
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in the allocated space – and much more interesting.
From the half-floor through the vintage copper light window from «Retrouvius» opens the view to the chic living room below.
Mirror furniture with a gold finish, silver accents and vintage luminaires from Serge Muy set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored protective panel looks like a window to another room.
At the entrance, the mirror cabinets are used to store all Joan's utensils.
To create the feeling of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can fence itself the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in the folding kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding up door, as in a garage.
“Here the engineering was involved,” Erfan tells about the steel-reinforced wood-fibre shield door.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan has received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
“In the end, the floor area is exactly what you’re going to sell, that is, what your property is valued at,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the area of the sexes.”
Here they were able to increase the floor area, using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the home,” Erfan says.
“Nobody falls in love with wiring in the walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t touch the strings of our hearts.”
This is a testament to the fact that, thanks to the good design and the increased meters, the apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
