Michelle Carter Sentenced for Reporting Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts resident has been sentenced to two and a half years in prison for inciting her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide by texting and calling.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will have to serve 15 months behind bars and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at a hearing Thursday: “My family was killed by grief.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at large until the appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum term of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, shaking hands and lowering his eyes.
"With her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
“She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
“She didn’t show any regrets.”
But Carter’s lawyer said it was “a tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, level of maturity, or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The prosecutor read Roy's mother Lynn Roy's statement, which read: "Not a single day has passed since I mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I'm doing - I'm trying to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will stay with us forever."
Roy’s sister, Camdin Roy, said she was haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or be the aunt of his children.
“Drowning the person who has been with me ever since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case would appear to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would hold a person responsible for advising him to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon dioxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stabb yourself with a knife, I don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and forbade her from speaking to the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
The views of the lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British neighbor's apartment in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old published in the Los Angeles Times her special opinion, stating: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prisons."
