Astronomers have found a "hell" planet on which even iron can melt
For the first time, after studying the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysicists were much surprised by its temperature, which is able to evaporate iron and other metals.
Experts have noticed that water molecules are so heated by starlight that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble telescope captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature causes the water in the planet's atmosphere to glow in the infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to the so-called "hot Jupiters" - gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet in the solar system, but located dozens of times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, the year on the exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "Earth" days, and its gas shell is hardened to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and southern France, but now there are fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender has become worse growing due to dry weather and disease-carrying insects; this has caused constant headaches for scientists and farmers trying to find a solution.
Eric Sess, an expert at CRIEPPAM, an agricultural research institute in Provence, said: “Lavender in Provence is really under threat because in recent years this plant has been feeling the effects of climate change: in the spring and especially in the fall the rains have become much less.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
And there are also small cicadas jumping on the leaves of insects that carry microbacteria; in very dry weather they become very many."
A lot has been put on the map.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is in high demand in perfumery and cosmetology.
Eric Sess says, “Instead of very long snails with a large number of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened, or absent ones.
Therefore, we have fewer parts containing essential oil.”
The solutions currently under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and removing varieties that are more drought-resistant.
