The killing of a journalist underscores that it is becoming more and more dangerous in Mexico.
Employees of the weekly newspaper "Riodos" usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to shed light on the latest violent crimes in Sinaloa state related to organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing war of drug dealers.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told to change their habits.
The two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking children with them to an office where they had already dropped a grenade in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote on the board hanging in the room, three words: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no evidence is needed, suspicion and inner feelings will suffice.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being detained by the government or by cartels, a whole list of scoundrels who are making it dangerous to expose chaos in Mexico.
Violence is not breathing, and among the corpses that are multiplying in the country, more and more journalists: according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people after the attacks and threats are under federal protection; and this year at least seven people have been killed.
Among the latter - their publisher and inspiring, the co-founder of "Riodas" Javier Valdes Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Valdes wrote in one of his numerous books on drug-related violent crimes.
His absence feels very acute, although his presence is everywhere - a large photograph of Valdez, showing the middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hanging on the facade of the building "Riodos"; two reporters of the 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, are wearing T-shirts, on which he is depicted.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their common trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, only two cases have been investigated so far, according to the Committee on the Protection of Journalists.
As is the case with most of the thousands of murders committed each year related to drug trafficking and organized crime, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Riodos journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are killed by grief, although it is now much more dangerous around.
“Without information about the killers, without justice from security talks at meetings, there is little use,” Ibarra says.
“It’s very stupid to spend time at this seminar,” he says.
“Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone.”
On the morning of May 15, Valdes left the office of Riodos in the capital of the state of Culiac<0xC3><0xA1>n.
He only managed to drive a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the name of the newspaper - which means "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove off in his car and smashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually spread quickly around Kuliakana.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdez.
Since Guzm<0xC3><0xA1>n was arrested and extradited to the United States in January last year, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlefields in the country as rival factions struggle to fill the resulting vacuum.
Not to mention that one or more people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with painted two-story mausoleums of drug lords, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Forget for a moment that the state of “quietness” is simply when one of the cartels takes control of the coastal state with important ports and routes of drug trafficking leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Waldes was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorquez, a 60-year-old co-founder and director of Rio de Janeiro, is crushed by a sense of guilt for failing to protect a friend.
He thinks that the murder was helped by two mistakes.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel, which is at war with the sons of Guzman.
The publication may have angered the sons; the people who were supposedly gang members bought all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he didn’t force Waldes to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that wrote about the same story was captured.
Waldes was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been out of danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroest and in 2003, together with five colleagues, founded Riodos, selling his $50 shares.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to engage in journalism without touching on the topic of drugs,” Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for courageous and honest publishing, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted that in this edition they could read about what no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Rio de Janeiro received the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for Reporting in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdes won the International Press Freedom Prize for his courage in investigating drug trafficking in Mexico, wherever it may lead.
He honestly admitted that he was scared.
"I want to live on," he said at the CPJ award ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is “a way of life,” he said in October last year in an interview with Rompeviento TV.
“You have to accept the tasks that lie on you as a journalist – either that or you’re just a fool.”
I don't want to be asked, "What did you do when there were so many deaths around... why didn't you tell me what was going on?"
The employees of Riodos miss Valdes, a joker who quarreled like a loader in a port, a friend, generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to get along alive.
They depended on the order they set.
He always had to wear his hat.
He was supposed to go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: has his love for the once-established order ruined him?
His death also caused them to question their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
“They don’t like it when you get to know their wives, their children, their legal business, and underground drug-carrying airports.
“These things were over the line,” Bohorkes said.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from what smells bad.
The problem, says Riodos editor Andrés Villarreal, is that “the deception can be deceived ... and then what happened to Javier happens.”
The old rules, he says, no longer work in Sinaloa — as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states, where there is a poisonous mixture of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where the employees of Rio de Janeiro gathered for security training, it was suddenly forbidden to bring mobile phones: a few days before it became known that spyware, which is sold exclusively to governments, is used in Mexico to monitor journalists and public activists.
Outside, two police officers hide in the shade of a tree from a 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were given the task of the state government to guard the office of “Riodos”, which is located in a four-storey building in the bourgeois quarter of Kuliakan.
Some journalists asked half-jokingly whether these policemen were among the 50 percent of the law and order that the governor himself said could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area that is de facto under the control of drug gangs.
In the next issue, "Riodos" counted on three main themes.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio César Chavez.
They also had the disclosure of government expenditures concentrated in the governor's hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping of people at one of the most expensive restaurants in Kuliakana, a block from the prosecutor's office.
It was not officially announced who was kidnapped or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was a favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered to a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of government for almost the past century.
Recently, several governors from the PRI have been loudly accused of corruption.
Villarreal asked reporters to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when Guzman’s son El Chapo escaped from the military raid.
A few months ago, readers would have searched for a column of Waldes with the most credible information about the kidnapping.
“We would have known before what happened,” says 46-year-old Villarreal, for his slim physique dubbed “El Flaco.”
“Today, all channels of communication with our sources are broken.”
Waldes’s office is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the killings of journalists because employees have become what they never thought they would become: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took several posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor’s office dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacan in the west of the country three days after he was killed by Waldes.
They found a burned body, and the authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Journalists across the country began to speak out louder, organize protests and write "SOS Press" on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
On that day, Director Bohorquez was in Washington, trying to secure international support for the demand for justice in the Waldes case.
At a meeting with Governor Sinaloa the day after Valdez’s murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their killing for telling the truth.
She then asked her not to give her any more information on the Government’s activities, fearing that anger would harm her objectivity.
Waldes has repeatedly said that journalists in Mexico are “surrounded” by organized crime, its accomplices in the government, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not just killed by gangs of drug traffickers; they do so on the orders of politicians and security services colluding with organized crime.
The Article 19 Press Protection Committee believes that half of the attacks on journalists last year were carried out by order of the police and government officials.
“In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,” Ramirez said.
Of course, murders frighten people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Masias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
On her body was found a note allegedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: “I’m here because of my articles.”
The computer keyboard and headphones were lying next to her severed head.
Some newspapers have preferred to close down, such as the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua, after its correspondent, Miroslav Brich, was killed in March.
Others continue to hold on as Nuevo Laredo’s “El Manjana” after the murder of its leader in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez publicly addressed drug cartels with an editorial on the front page titled “What do you want from us?”
Some journalists have left their home states or the country at all.
It's a painful decision.
In exile, it is difficult to find work, and they are still looking for danger in the streets.
And they are sometimes killed, as apparently happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work balance daily between risky decisions.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he is afraid to write about drug trafficking.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that’s why I became a journalist,” he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was ready for printing, the publishers of "Riodos" sat on the sidewalk next to the office and drank beer when suddenly their phones rang at the same time.
A series of shootings between opposing gangs and security forces near the resort town of Masatlan left behind 19 bodies, according to confirmed data.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of messages from cartels discovered in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted the news via their mobile phone on the website of "Riodos".
The next day I had to revisit the first page.
Sirens roared nearby - another shooting in the vicinity.
Bohorkes looked to see if the police guards were ready to defend them.
If they were scared, they didn’t show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was exposed to the sight of the whole of Sinaloa, the employees of "Riodos" continued his case.
"How can you think of closing," said Bohorkes, "if on the same day that Javier was killed, the trainee asked me to send her out to report?"
The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies.
At first glance, it appears to be a statue, although it is horrifying.
The researchers said the first found remains of a rhinoceros-sized creature found by a Canadian miner survived so well that experts called it “My Lisa Among Dinosaurs.”
It was so well preserved that they could even determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown — and say that he had, in a way, a “dark past.”
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as "the best-preserved of Thyreophorus in the history of the finds and one of the best specimens of the dinosaur in the world".
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaurus that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good condition has stunned researchers who call him “really remarkable.”
This herbivorous thyrophore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
He was found by Sean Fank when he was working at the Sancor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed different from the surrounding breed, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil discovered by him was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out to detect an animal inside a 2,500-foot (1,100-kg) earthen fungus.
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
“It’s only worth a little snooze, and you can almost believe that he’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is shown.
“It will enter the history of science as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved specimens of dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs.”
Studying his skin, the researchers found that it was herbivorous, despite the fact that it was covered with armor and resembled a walking tank, apparently exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective paint, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow it to merge more quickly with the environment and avoid encountering enemies, experts say, assuming it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the nodosaur family, was widely illuminated in the press in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum lab worker Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group who spent more than 7,000 hours excavating it.
The astonishing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the drawing and shape of scales and armor plates on his body.
They discovered a protective paint, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its bottom.
Although protective coloring is common, the discovery came as a surprise, because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is significantly larger than the size of the currently living animals with protective coloring.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to disguise confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective paint—such as deer, zebras, or armored animals—are much smaller in size and are more affordable prey, suggesting that the nodosaurus had to fight seriously for survival.
“A serious threat from predators to a massive, powerful dinosaur armored creature shows just how dangerous Melo period predator dinosaurs were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in the dinosaur’s scale also suggests that its skin was supposed to be reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal in search of information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was carried into the sea, where it sank and with its back down lay on the bottom of the ocean.
At the time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans likely spread far deeper into the land than they do now.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time is completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the animal’s original shape,” Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it looked then, in the Early Mellow Period.
You don’t have to use your imagination to recreate it, you just have to snooze a little, and you can almost believe that it’s asleep.”
The Mela period is the era when giant theropods, flesh-eating dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, the tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, the thyreophorus could have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
These include the acrocantosaurus, a 38-foot-long (11.5-meter) monster weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose latest findings are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was taken to the sea after death and mummified in the ivy.
The creature was found by Sean Fank when he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum’s staff, it is the best-preserved thyrophore in the world, along with the skin and armor, and it’s all the way from the muzzle to the thigh bones.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
The researchers believe that this herbivorous thyrophore has been hard hit by what is now Canada until the spilling river carried it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved his armor with precision to the smallest detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen have been preserved so well that the remains of the skin still cover the crumpled armor plates along the dinosaur’s skull.
As Michael Mishko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is “rare as winning a lottery.”
The longer I look at him, the more striking he seems.
The fossilized remains of the skin still cover the crumpled armor plates that soak up the animal’s skull.
His right front leg is stretched along the side, five fingers on it are turned upside down.
I can count the scales on his sole.”
