There were photos of the signal tape and screaming people and the man who claimed to be Brown’s father, holding a poster saying, “A Ferguson cop just killed my unarmed son!”
She watched a live broadcast as a police officer stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, took a shotgun and shouted, “I’ll kill you all...animals!”
“It’s a non-standard situation,” Ferrell said at the time, according to her own memoirs.
“It’s not murder like the ones we’re used to and we can call typical.
At that moment, I felt cold.
I was angry and I was crying.”
She took a return ticket and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11 p.m., she took her six-year-old daughter out of her father's house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next almost three years became the subject of the new documentary “Whose Streets?”, which will be released on August 11.
It is a story about survival and protest, about love and loss, strength and endurance from the point of view of people living in a community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
While Ferrell was traveling to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower dress and a wreath of color, they remembered the conversation that had taken place before this morning countless times, “about the experience of the blacks and their position.”
She recalls saying, “Do you remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We’re going to Ferguson right now because a policeman killed an 18-year-old boy, and that was wrong.”
“I couldn’t help but take it,” Ferrell said later.
“What is happening today is the culmination of what happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it, and grow up on it.
She must not only understand activism and organization well, but also understand the different levels of experience of blacks and their positions and what we must do to become free in order to be liberated.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she herself will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would have done her a disservice if I had stopped her from doing it.”
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop on South Florissant Road, on the site across the road from a police station that had become something of a tent camp, while activists were waiting for reports of officer Derren Uil’s final indictment.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined a local businessman who cooked lunch packages.
They collected the bags and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Little by little, Ferrell took the form of a new type of activism.
“My activism has completely changed since August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was the president of the Association of Student Healthy People, a national minority, and engaged in food justice and health inequalities among blacks.
“I didn’t have the experience of an organizer.
It came by itself.”
A few weeks later, at the evening demonstration, Ferrel met Sabaa Folayan, one of her directors.
Folayan said she and her chief operator, Lucas Alvarado-Ferrer, "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell came up with the question: “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?”
This skepticism was infused with numerous people, often white, who came to the community in order to benefit from its pain and endurance.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson were not in the spotlight, and they wanted to do it differently.”
By that time, Folayan had teamed up with her director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row issues.
His involvement aroused a sense of sympathy for Ferrell and six other local residents with whom the Whose Streets? project team had been in touch for years after Brown’s murder.
“In this documentary, no one speaks for us or with us, we speak for ourselves,” Davis said.
“It was the most important thing to me about how these people will be represented, because that’s how I’ll be represented.”
And although the goal of the project was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - in an effort to show that the movement "is not about the leader-savior, but about how the community unites", as Folayan said - it turned out to be the most open of the participants in the film.
As a result, Whose Streets? shows unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell said, laughing about seeing the finished product for the first time.
“But I realized that when you do that kind of work and humanize black people, there has to be some level of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell’s story again discusses and emphasizes the role of a black homosexual woman in the broader context of the “Life of Black Matters” movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement — those who created the #BlackLivesMatter tag on social media after the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin — classify themselves as homosexuals.
“Black homosexual women in leadership positions support all this movement,” Ferrell says, “because we are constantly fighting on several fronts.
Black gay women have to bear all of this burden.”
Folayan agreed with this claim, noting that “the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of gay black women.”
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination", and that Ferrell was not chosen as the central character of the film due to its distinctive features.
“She was the person who awakened that energy,” she said.
“On the other hand, it’s no coincidence that she was in the foreground because when”
You can feel her energy through the screen.”
Meanwhile, Ferguson has long been without film cameras, but there remain complex racial ties between the community and the police.
Ferrel will be on probation for another two-and-a-half years for shutting down the highway during the demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place she calls home, simply: “Bardak.”
She's still holding on to the speech she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson full three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
