The emergence of similarity: the artist creates portraits with the help of the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York, the faces of people hanging from the ceiling on the wire - white, black and brown, all somewhat elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek smears and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Levenworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous transmission of confidential diplomatic telegrams on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The Emergence of Similarity".
This is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident whom Barack Obama softened just three days before the end of his presidency.
Analyzing the DNA from Manning's computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that could be in people with such a genome, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, albeit not easy-to-perceive, intuitive manifesto devoted not only to the plasticity of their DNA data, but also to the intuitability of their DNA data.
Manning, who was born under the name of Bradley Edward, but since her teenage years has said openly that she considers herself a woman, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Espionage, Computer Fraud and Theft Act.
Her photographs in prison were inaccessible, so only one of her photographs was known: a grainy black and white selfie, in which Manning in a platinum shade wig, clearly feeling awkward, sat behind the wheel of the car; with this photograph she began to be associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg completed her 2012 project "Visions of Strangers" with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people with the help of judicial evidence such as cloves and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this rubbish and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new exhibition for the press.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she would like to have a portrait made of her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her prison muse became correspondence friends and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book entitled Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoaly Kanungo, which depicted how the president would ease Chelsea’s punishment in the future and be able to visit the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama really decided to release Manning just a few days after the book came out was a pleasant surprise after seven tough years in a Kansas military prison.
There’s something profound and powerful about the exhibition opening right now as Donald Trump declares war on people revealing secret information in the government and invents new ways to inflame the enmity he’s meant to soften on Twitter.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the timing of all this, she said that "nothing happens by chance."
In a statement written on the gallery wall, Manning’s huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a dot above the “i” in her name) calls for an end to “automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation, and culture.”
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist scientifically excels), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how surprisingly similar we are, at least in our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open genetic data is for interpretation, and how subjective it is,” said Dewey-Harborg; her 2007 video work, False Memories, is also featured here.
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exposition, which fits in one room, is the aforementioned novel in the comics.
On it, King Kong-style Manning appears above the U.S. Correctional Barracks building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
“Never be silent.”
“It’s a direct quote from the letter she wrote to me,” says the artist who greeted us from Philadelphia.
“I still have ants on my skin when I talk about it.”
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person — as it was visually depicted in the comics — but when it arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genome-like simulacrums gathering like crowds of protesters.
This was also done intentionally, like everything on the exhibition up to the height (5"2, Manning's height), on which the pencil was drawn genetic haplogroups.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people,” Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
“I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like the movement that was behind her liberation.”
