Startups that will help your company not become another “Uber”
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among employees of her startup in the field of e-commerce, but the surveys did not work.
The answers were often vague, pointless, or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“It’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who manages San Francisco-based 75-person Madison Reed, a hair care e-commerce firm.
Therefore, she appealed to third parties for help.
Now, a new type of startups in the field of personnel work is emerging that help companies find out how their employees feel.
By designing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to do express surveys, address specific teams and demographics, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow informants to go to the top.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, but where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City startup Glint, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she had achieved a greater understanding of what her employees were thinking and feeling during the three years of using Glent.
In addition to express surveys and surveys of certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form, which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
The companies are becoming more and more aware that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another Uber, who was involved in a scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction, the order.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to estimates from the Internet portal “Let’s Talk About Payment”, dedicated to financial technologies, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a startup in Denver, Colorado, that helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid the decline in Uber’s reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send custom-made surveys of staff opinions, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
“The court of public opinion has seized power from inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company mistreats employees or behaves unethically, even if the inspector does not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, outflows of employees and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees at 500 locations, has used Convercent for over a year to ensure employees are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer an easy way to contact the company’s head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for the phone number or email of the head office, file an official complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of law at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company uses the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, harassment, and unfair pay — can be found and dealt with more quickly.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday network’s risk management team.
“And we are protecting our shareholders from litigation with employees.”
According to Quinland, companies began to take employees’ ethics, values and involvement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen’s accounting firm collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron case.
But it wasn’t until “social media got widespread,” that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty linens from spreading virally online.
“Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both “Glint” and “Convercent” offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glent received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising if you take into account the interconnected nature of companies, culture, and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, this is just the necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated, and that they dedicate their time to the company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work for a company, feel that they are heard, and that the work they do brings results, they are more trying to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn.
Investors make a profit when business with companies from their portfolio goes well; business with companies goes well when employees are committed and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee involvement.
But the data is useless until the company’s custodians take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if the changes don’t come quickly enough, or don’t come at all, disappointment can develop, and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 offers, you should be prepared to have 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at Kotter International, which had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, the staff will wonder, ‘Did you really hear me?
Don't you care?
If you don’t care, why shouldn’t I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem with the help of Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees, dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve the problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it to retain employees more effectively in an industry known for its high staff fluency.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
