This is not the first book by Rhodes that is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man’s Teeth and Other Stories, a collection of British Library materials; this project unexpectedly touched him to the core.
“I could have been touched by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites,” he said.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those times the fire was lit for lighting.
And in 300 years, in the future, you feel like you’re there too.
I love the archives!"
For a person with such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in the castle for four months ("Honestly, I've had a bit of a stay there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent all day studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and looking at numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had been in the trenches for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to woodworkers, gardeners, and sometimes artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drank whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotty’s castle has not been fully explored because the National Fund only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassi, died.
When Rods arrived there ten years later, the staff were only beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as "what aristocrats have been putting on the loft for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, "but there were two families fighting over this birch.
That's what happens, guys!"
In some stories of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for wider explorations in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There is information about the rebellion that occurred in the castle in 1380, in a book called ‘Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,’” says Rods.
“The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought the uprising was a good start.
“Maybe they were connected?”
Other plots are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest", which tells about a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid in his house for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or “The Smuggler,” about the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling the tomb with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the tomb was dug).
Darrell is Rods' favorite family of all who inhabited Scotty: "The gentlemen seem to have been a perfect swindler, forever getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, the Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women — I imagine them as the company of nice guys who know how to care for the heirs of great fortunes.
After finishing work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish dugout, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamyanmyaki - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it again grew into a forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he says.
“I felt like this: Damn it, I have to go back to real life again.”
