Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help alleviate CKD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the intestines make sure that harmful microbes that come with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and at the same time not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in the intestine have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan — one of the building blocks of protein — to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of a normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of tolerance-enhancing cells.
The more tryptophan in the mice’s diet, the more of these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: the combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan may contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation environment in the gut.
Postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and another group, which belonged to the same line but was contained separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice—communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestinal cells of mice was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice that had immune cells but were absent in mice that did not.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cell, received L. reuteri, and the immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of the fluid — without bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells secreted from mice.
Immune cells have been converted into tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the food of mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells also fell by twice.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found.
She says, "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may potentially lead to an expansion of their population.”
