"Mamaev is the organizer of the robbery, which also forms the composition of the crime, and, accordingly, such a person should be brought to criminal liability," said Uliana Solopova, a spokesman for the Moscow court.
In this case, the court took into account the state of health of Mamaev, the actual circumstances of the case, the absence of aggravating circumstances.
In addition, the court applied Article 64 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation, according to which a punishment below the lower limit can be imposed.
As for Mamaev’s assistant Vasily Serosthanov, the court did not establish circumstances that would be the basis for changing the category of severity of the sentence committed and changing the sentence.
Anton Mamaev himself said that he remained dissatisfied with the decision of the Moscow court.
I'm disappointed with the court's decision.
The only legitimate solution would be justification, intending to continue to fight for justice.
His lawyer Andrey Orlov did not rule out appealing the sentence in the Moscow Court of Cassation and the Supreme Court.
“We will use all the levers up to the European Court of Human Rights,” he told RIA Novosti.
Recall that 28-year-old Muscovite Anton Mamaev, suffering from spinal muscular atrophy, became a criminal case last fall.
