Requisite for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to deploy a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One" when the president is on board, became the central element of the July 17 White House event that showcased U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials have inspected technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Corps Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the division in charge of the helicopter, the military administration of the White House ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the "southern lawn".
“I just wanted you to make sure you were aware because this is an unusual, widely reported event,” HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his chief, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in the event scheduled for 3 p.m. of the day, and would remain there until the lawn would be cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the operating hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by the magazine "TIME", it was not clear whether the second crew was required in the end.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal officials from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 has clarified whether the event is in conflict with the decree.
“Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“You seem to have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The “Made in America” event was declared by the White House as an official event and was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even the official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to promote the health reform that was being developed in the Senate at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But asking them only in the interest of photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump had already become the subject of discussion in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first pre-election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is thrilled with the ‘Made in America’ show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsey Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with an accuracy of up to an inch.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the event “Made in America” was counted by the crew as the necessary training flights for a month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of “non-presidential support missions.”
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not pay for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Department of Defense compensation rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit records that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes to each side from its airfield base at the Quantico Marine Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“Calculating the cost for taxpayers, based on an approximate rate of reimbursement, is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These sample rates include staffing, service and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by REND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, services and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in favor of using the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things done in America,” Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
Therefore, it is, of course, entirely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while looking at the South Lawn during the event, but he was exactly sitting in the driver’s seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, jokingly with the press on the topic of his own fleet of products of the company.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said.
